      "content": "# StructuredUniform\n\n`StructuredUniform` is a schema-typed uniform buffer for custom WebGPU pipelines.\nIt uses the same string-literal uniform schema dialect as `material()` and the\nsame WGSL alignment machinery, but it does not create a render pipeline or force a\nfixed bind group shape. Use it when you need a generated uniform-buffer ABI while\nstill composing your own bind groups, blend state, render targets, or shader\nentry points.\n\n## Constructor\n\n```ts\nconst params = new StructuredUniform(device, {\n  label: \"scene-params\",\n  schema: {\n    viewProj: \"mat4x4f\",\n    cameraPos: \"vec3f\",\n    time: \"f32\",\n  },\n  visibility: [\"vertex\", \"fragment\"], // optional; default is vertex + fragment\n});\n```\n\n- `schema`: non-empty record of field names to `WgslUniformType` values. Field\n  insertion order is the WGSL struct member order.\n- `label`: optional debug label for the backing buffer and the lazy bind group\n  objects.\n- `visibility`: shader stages for the lazy binding-0 layout. Pass\n  `GPUShaderStageFlags`, a string, or an array such as `[\"compute\"]`.\n\nSupported field types are the same flat uniform types supported by `material()`:\n`f32`, `u32`, `i32`, `vec2f`, `vec3f`, `vec4f`, `vec2u`, `vec3u`, `vec4u`,\n`vec2i`, `vec3i`, `vec4i`, `mat3x3f`, and `mat4x4f`. Nested structs and arrays\nare intentionally out of scope for v1.\n\n## Members\n\n- `structured.schema`: the original schema object.\n- `structured.layout`: `UniformLayoutInfo` with fields, offsets, and byte size.\n  This is exposed so future layout validation can consume the generated ABI.\n- `structured.byteSize`: the derived uniform struct byte size.\n- `structured.offsets`: byte offsets keyed by schema field name.\n- `structured.buffer`: the VGPU `Buffer` wrapper, created with\n  `uniform | copy_dst` usage.\n- `structured.gpu`: the underlying `GPUBuffer`, so `bind.resource(0, structured)`\n  works anywhere a VGPU buffer-like object is accepted.\n- `structured.bindGroupLayout` / `structured.bindGroup`: lazy binding-0 uniform\n  layout and bind group for the common one-buffer case.\n- `structured.destroy()` / `structured.dispose()` / `structured[Symbol.dispose]()`:\n  release the backing buffer once; idempotent.\n\n## Partial writes\n\n`write()` accepts a partial object and merges it into a zero-initialized CPU\nscratch buffer. Missing keys keep their previous values. Every call uploads the\nwhole uniform buffer in one `queue.writeBuffer` call.\n\n```ts\nparams.write({ viewProj, cameraPos: eye });\nparams.write({ time: performance.now() / 1000 }); // viewProj/cameraPos persist\n```\n\nScalars must be numbers. Vector and matrix fields accept arrays, `Float32Array`,\n`Uint32Array`, or `Int32Array`; `write()` checks the exact runtime length. For\nexample, `vec3f` must receive\nexactly three values and `mat3x3f` must receive exactly nine values. `mat3x3f`\nvalues are expanded into WGSL's 16-byte column stride, so the padding cannot drift\nfrom the generated layout.\n\nUnknown keys throw `VGPU-CORE-INVALID-USAGE`, which catches field-name typos at\nfirst write.\n\n## WGSL generation\n\n`wgsl(structName = \"Uniforms\")` emits only the struct declaration. Add your own\n`@group` / `@binding` line to match the bind group that consumes the buffer.\n\n```ts\nconst shader = `${params.wgsl(\"Params\")}\n@group(0) @binding(0) var<uniform> params: Params;\n${body}`;\n```\n\nExample output:\n\n```wgsl\nstruct Params {\n  viewProj: mat4x4<f32>,\n  cameraPos: vec3<f32>,\n  time: f32,\n};\n```\n\n## Composing into custom bind groups\n\nUse the lazy bind group for the simple one-buffer case:\n\n```ts\npass.setBindGroup(0, params.bindGroup);\n```\n\nOr compose the buffer into a larger bind group:\n\n```ts\nconst group = createBindGroup(device, {\n  layout,\n  entries: [\n    bind.resource(0, params),\n    bind.resource(1, texture),\n    bind.resource(2, sampler),\n  ],\n});\n```\n\n## Group by update frequency\n\nGroup uniforms by **update frequency**, not by conceptual domain. Use one\n`StructuredUniform` per update tier:\n\n| Tier | Contents | Write cadence |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Per-frame | camera, time, DPR, global lighting | once per frame |\n| Per-pass / per-draw | pass kind, blend params | once per pass or draw |\n| Rarely-changing | material constants, grid config | on interaction only |\n\n`queue.writeBuffer` has fixed per-call overhead, each `setBindGroup` is a state\nchange, and default WebGPU limits (`maxUniformBuffersPerShaderStage = 12`,\n`maxBindGroups = 4`) make many tiny uniform buffers expensive. A single\nmega-uniform is the opposite trap: changing one per-pass field can force repeated\nmid-frame rewrites or duplication. One struct per tier avoids both extremes.\n\n## Relationship to `material()` and `Uniform`\n\n`material()` is still the quickest path when its fixed pipeline shape works for\nyour renderer. `StructuredUniform` is for custom pipelines that still want the\nsame schema-to-layout safety.\n\n`Uniform` is a raw byte buffer helper: you provide the byte size and packed data.\n`StructuredUniform` derives byte size and offsets from a schema and writes fields\nby name.\n\n## Not in v1\n\n`StructuredUniform.slots()` is described as a v1.1 follow-up in the original\nproposal and is not included in v1. Use `UniformPool` for streaming per-draw ring\nallocation today, or create multiple `StructuredUniform` instances when you need\nstable per-pass values before the slots helper lands.\n"
